migrations in the same run are attempted.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The real failure is transaction + control-flow interaction (apply migration, handle SQL error, rollback, stop pipeline). A Unit test of error branching alone misses rollback semantics and stop-after-failure handoff. System is not required because this can be reproduced in-process with local DB wiring; no AI/ML or multi-agent steps apply.","test_description":"Prepare two migrations where the first contains multiple statements with one guaranteed SQL error after an initial write, and the second would add a detectable side effect. Run runner against test PostgreSQL and assert: first migration side effects are absent (rolled back), second migration was not applied, and only expected failure metadata/logging is present.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.25,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When two instances of the runner start at the same time against the same database, each migration is applied exactly once across both instances.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This behavior’s failure mode is real concurrent process interaction (separate processes + DB locking/race timing). Mocked or single-process tests can hide inter-process race conditions, transaction isolation edge cases, and lock acquisition timing. No AI/ML dependency, so not Agentic/Workflow.","test_description":"Launch two real Node.js runner processes simultaneously against the same PostgreSQL instance and the same migrations directory (including at least one migration with a visible side effect). Wait for both to finish, then assert each migration appears once in `_migrations` and each migration side effect exists exactly once.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.92,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"descrip